Creating intricate Islamic geometric designs using Go programming language requires a good understanding of the underlying mathematical principles and algorithms used in Islamic art. One way to create such designs is to use a library such as "gogeo" or "go-cairo" that provides support for drawing geometric shapes and patterns.
Here is some sample Go code that uses the "gogeo" library to create a simple Islamic geometric design:
```
package main
import (
    "github.com/fogleman/gg"
    "github.com/tidwall/gjson"
)
func main() {
    const (
        S = 1000 // size of the canvas
        M = 50   // margin
        N = 8    // number of sides
    )
    // create a new context for drawing
    dc := gg.NewContext(S, S)
    dc.SetRGB(1, 1, 1)
    dc.Clear()
    // draw a regular polygon with N sides
    x, y := S/2, S/2
    r := S/2 - M
    dc.NewSubPath()
    for i := 0; i < N; i++ {
        a := float64(i)*2*gg.PI/float64(N) - gg.PI/2
        px, py := x+r*math.Cos(a), y+r*math.Sin(a)
        dc.LineTo(px, py)
    }
    dc.ClosePath()
    dc.SetRGB(0, 0, 0)
    dc.SetLineWidth(2)
    dc.Stroke()
    // create a pattern of overlapping circles
    for i := 0; i < N; i++ {
        a := float64(i)*2*gg.PI/float64(N) - gg.PI/2
        px, py := x+r*math.Cos(a), y+r*math.Sin(a)
        dc.NewSubPath()
        for j := 0; j < 4; j++ {
            b := float64(j)*gg.PI/2 + a
            cx, cy := px+(r/2)*math.Cos(b), py+(r/2)*math.Sin(b)
            dc.DrawCircle(cx, cy, r/4)
            dc.Fill()
        }
    }
    // save the image to a file
    dc.SavePNG("design.png")
    // analyze the design using gjson library
    json := `{"design": {"name": "Islamic geometric design", "style": "Almohad", "construction": "Geometric principles"}}`
    value := gjson.Get(json, "design.style")
    println(value.String())
}
```
This code creates a regular polygon with eight sides and draws a pattern of overlapping circles on each vertex. The resulting image is saved to a PNG file called "design.png". The code also uses the "gjson" library to analyze the design by extracting the value of the "style" field from a JSON object.
